{"/service/ndnp/fu/batch_fu_calhoun_ver01/data/sn83016244/00513689925/1958042401/0598.xml":{"full_text":"F\nTNI KEY WEST CITIUM Thursday, April 24, IMS\nPage 6\nThe Key West Citizen\nPublished Sunday Morning and Every Week Day Afternoon,\nExcept Saturday\nwn wowwwTa Circulation Manager\nCURRY Meehan Irai Buperlntendent\nMEMBER OF ASSOCIATED PRESS\nCatered al Key Wear Florida an\nSeeond Claae Matter\nCARRIER SUBSCRIPTION RATES\nYear\n6 Montha i....\nI \u2014r- \u2019R\nMAIL RATES aiaaa\n1 Year\nf Month. -J?\nI Montho ..ii\n<Me weekly mail eubocriptTone Aoc.ntadf\nNATIONAL ADVERTISING REPRESENTATIVES:\nTHBIB A BIMPHON. CO INC.\nI E. 14th BL. New York SI. N. Y.\nBranch Orfloae In Principal Cities\nThe Nation Salutes\nFollowers Of Hippocrates\nThe entire nation la observinf Medical Education\nWeek through April 26. Medical association! and\nschools of medicine throughout the country point with\njustifiable pride to the accomplishments and advance\nof medicine through education and research.\nDue to the contribution of all phases of medicine\nin the last 50 years, the life span of the average Ameri*\ncan has been increased by 20 years.\nGlance at the remarkable record which has been\nestablished by medical education in the past two decades\nand which has made the United States the healthiest\nnation in the world.\nEpidemics of yellow fever, typhus and cholera have\nbeen cut to rare and isolated cases. Contagious diseases\nsuch as small pox and diptheria have practically been\neliminated. Polio, thanks to medical science and patient\nresearch, is largely under control.\nTuberculosis still haunts communities, especially\nslum areas; but it is not as widespread as in the past.\nVenereal disease is not stamped out, but modern treat\nments have checked its inroads when discovered in\ntime. Public health measures have been responsible for\nthis.\nHeart disease is still the number one killer, but new\nsystems in treatment of cardiac affliction, and brand\nnew surgical techniques, are cutting down on the toll of\nvictims. This is especially true in care of children who\nhave congenital heart defects.\nCancer currently.remains the enigma, but even In\nthis difficult field, advances are being made due to\nmedical research and the accent on early diagnosis.\nThe use of insulin in treatment of diabetes has\nreached the point where most patients are able to carry\non in normal activities.\nOver >2OO million dollars went into maintenance\nof medical schools during the past year. Students who\nare to be the physicians, dentists, pharmacists, research\ners and technicians of the future, were not the only\npersonnel to benefit by the program.\nMedical colleges also help in keeping the estab\nlished doctors, surgeons, specialists and general prac\ntioners, alert to the latest advances through medical\neducation.\nThe pther evening, a Key West physician, who was\nasked why he kept on with gruelling hours and work\nthat afforded him little relaxation, answered simply,\nwith quiet pride, \u201cJ am a doctor.'*\nAs long as we have inspiring, dedicated, medical\nmen like that, we can face the complex problems which\ncome with the atomic age with more confidence.\nMedical education points the way to longer, hap\npier lives despite turmoil in the universe. The ancient\noath of Hippocrates, pioneer Greek physician, is still\nInspirational promise to mankind.\nIn Grand Rapids, Mich., police give motorists a do\nit-yourself kit to tell whether they've drunk too much\nto drive. But what if a man has drunk too much to be\nable to operate the teat kit?\nPresident Eisenhower is doing a lot these days to\nget baseball on its feet, First he tipped off one of the\nbig league teams about a hot prospect\u2014the son of a\nWhite Hopse aide. Then he opened the season for the\nSenators\u2014and they won, 5 to 2.\ng Crossword Puzzle\nAOBOM\n1. Heroic\nA Panto\nH.FortWea\nHa\n11 Apportions\n14. Shun\n11 Perusing\nIT. Malia\n11 Vigilant\n14. Bluegrass\nM. Augment\n11. Inclination\n11 Saucy\n11 Wanted\nIS. Social\n.group\nM. Maas eape\nIT. Sport\nML Under\n11. Luck\n11 Wolfhound\n11 Sato\nIT. And not\nM. Brink\nM. Spoken\n40. Prime\ndonna\n41. Cooking\nvessel\n43. Instances\n44. Infuriate\n43. Solitary\n44. Woeda\n47. Persian\ncoin\nDOWN\nl.rixed\nfirmly\n1 Rescind 1\n1 Idolises\nSolution of Yeaterday'a Puulo\n4. Self-com*\nplacent\n5. Outcome\n1 Kind of\nrifle\nT. On one's\ntoes\nWASHINGTON Right now\nwe're having one of the greatest\nguessing games in history: Should\ntaxes be cut now to fight the re*\ncession? Our future* is involved in\nthe right answer.\nAnswers are coming from mem-'\nben of both political parties, econ\nomists, individuals, private groups\nbusinessmen, labor. Since every*\none can\u2019t be right, someone's\nguessing.\nThe variety of their response\ngives an emphatic no to any idea\nthat economics in the year 1958\nis an exact science.\nThe Eisenhower administration\nand the Democratic leaders in\nCongress are both playing cau\ntious. They're waiting to see If\nthe recession gets worse before\ngoing for a tax cut.\nSecretary of the Treasury An\nderson and the Democratic leader\nof the House, Speaker Rayburn of\nTexas, have a gentlemen's agree\nment to consult with each other\nbefore either takes the initiative\non a cut.\nBut the U. S. Chamber of Com\nmerce, the National Assn, of Man\nufacturers, and the AFL-CIO are\nfor a reduction now, although they\ndiffer on the kind of cuts they\nwant.\nFormer President Truman, an\namateur economist, wants fast\naction. So Does Sen. Douglas, Illi\nnois Democrat, a professional\neconomist of national standing be\nfore his election to Congress.\nBernard M. Baruch, advisor to\npresidents from Wilson to Eisen\nhower, considers a tax reduction\nunthinkable. Not so Marriner S.\nEccles, who headed the Federal\nReserve Board under Presidents\nRoosevelt and Truman. He's for a\ncut.\nBut Secretary Anderson, who\n\u25a0seems to be guiding the adminis\ntration's wait-and-see policy, has\nrepeatedly urged caution. He\u2019s got\nsomething to worry about. A tax\ncut of five billion dollars would\nadd to his woes by adding to the\nnational debt.\nEven without a tax cut, he fore\ncast last week, the government's\ndeficit this year will be over three\nbillion dollars. v\nYet over the weekend a highly\nrespected private group \u2014a panel\nof 17 businessmen, economists and\neducators Issued a report for\nthe Rockefeller Brothers Fund.\nThey called for quick action in\ni. Kin\nSeed\nholder\n10. Cyestalk\n13. Harsh\nnasal sound\n11 Portal\n11 Unwanted\n11. Forehead\nIt. Breathe\nquickly\n14. Sacred\nImago\nM. Short*\nspoken\n17. Unfair\n31 Shuts out\n31 The chosen\n30. Bewail\n31. Blases\n'll. Sounding\ntogether\n11. Nino days'\ndevotion\n14. Rubber\n34. Raw silk\n34. Persian\npoet\n40. Sp. pointer\n41. Conatolla*\ntion\n41 Bounder\nHOPING IT GETS INTO ORBIT\nJr\nyliirw\nK TA\nJHA\n17.3 Kyapc/J\nxO wS.-\nW '-'7.\nr- I \\i 1\nThe World\nToday\nBy JAMBS MARLOW\nME SURE... with a\nmBHF Jfth FLORID A National\nGHMMIH checking account\nHousehold money is easier to keep track of\nwhen you use a Florida National checking account.\nYour canceled check is your receipt. Don't wonder whether\nyou have paid a bill or not... know by using a Florida check\ning account. Opep your account today at the Florida National.\nFLORIDA National Bank\neas urns to in komm hmiohm cmm. \u25a0aaaaa nrw _ _\nH\nMEMBER FEDERAL DEPOSIT INSURANCE CORPORATION\nseveral directions, Including a tax\ncut.\u2019\nThese are just some of the dif\nferences in opinion. Why the dif\nferences?\nThere's danger in holding off\non a cut to see if the recession\ngets.worse: if it does, and snow\nballs, a tax reduction might be too\nlate to do.good. But there\u2019s also\ndanger in chopping taxes too soon.\nIf they were reduced just as the\neconomy was taking an-upturn,\nthey might cause Inflation which\nin the end would be worse than\nthe present recession. When is the\nupturn expected? No agreement\non that either.\nOver the weekend Secretary of\nCommerce Weeks said he thought\nthe bottom had been reached al\nthough the upturn might not start\nuntil fall.\nTwo Communists Shot\nTEHRAN, Iran (!>\u2014Two former\nmembers of Iran\u2019s outlawed Com\nmunist party, Hushang Pour Rez\nvan and Arsen Awanesian, were\nshot at dawn yesterday.\nThey were convicted of anti\nsecurity activities and member\nship in the illegal party.\nInvest Safely In Florida\nThe Mackie Plan makes it easy to buy land\nwhere Florida\u2019s future is brightest\nPORT CHARLOTTE\nSeveral lots have already been sold to\nKey Westers and several blocks are\nbeing reserved especially for Key West.\nA big 80\u2019 x 125\u2019 Lot is 8795 810 down and\n810 a month. For full information, contact\nMR. GONZALO BEZANILLA\nat CY 6-6911 or CY 6-5792\nCARLOS VILLA. Realtor 1744 S.W. 3rd AVENUE\nMIAMI, FLORIDA\nHe Should Have\nPaid Last Year\nLOS ANGELES (!)-When Nor\nris Freeman drove out of Jules\nRay's garage last year he owed a\nglO bill, Ray testified in Small\nClaims Court.\nRay jumped in his car and gave\nchase. The cars collided, and\nFreeman was billed for $9O dam\nages to Ray's auto. Small Claims\nCourt upheld Ray\u2019s .claim.\nFreeman appealed. Superior'\nCourt upheld the lower court's\nruling. Freeman was ordered to\npay $lOO to the garage, plus $l6O\njury fees and $2B court costs.\nFreeman paid.\nPuts Arm Out; Loses\n$BOO Worth Of Jewelry\nCLEVELAND (!)\u2014A woman told\npolice here that a man snatched\na diamond ring and wrist watch\nshe was Wearing when she ex\ntended her arm from her car sig\nnaling a left turn.\nMrs. Ray L. Maylin, 37, of sub\nurban Cleveland 1 Heights, said she\nhad stopped for a traffic light and\nhad her left arm out for the turn\nwhen a man grabbed her arm and\nstripped the jewelry from her.\nShe valued it at $BOO.\nMrs. Maylin said the man then\ngot into a car and drove off.\nPorcupines are devastating men\naces to tree farmers for porcu\npines' favorite dessert is to chew\nup a healthy young tree. More\nover, reports one Oregon tree\nfarmer, they will eat anything,\nincluding dynamite.\nHal Boyle Says\nNEW YORK Things a\ncolumnist might never know if be\ndidn\u2019t open his mail:\nThat grandpa and grandma\nwere only half as likely to live to\ncelebrate their golden wedding\nanniversary as a young couple\nmarrying today. The chances in\n1900 that a bridegroom of 25 and\na bride of 21 would survive 50\nmore years was only 123 per\n1,000 marriages. Now it\u2019s 29S per\n1,000.\nThat the Eskimos have no na\ntive word for snow.\nThat 14 million American men\ncan\u2019t swim. But this doesn\u2019t ex\nplain our own sinking feeling.\nThat the first hospitals were es\ntablished,in Ceylon five centuries\nbefore Christ. Incidentally, the\nfederal government now owns 432\nhospitals with a total of more than\n184.000 beds.\nThat there is a hardware dealer\nin The Bronx named J. Rohs\nThat singer Lisa Kirk points out\na man \"can \u2018marry a fashion\nplate and still not get a nice\ndish.\u2019\u2019\nThat since the dawn of time the\nmost popular color for decorating\nhas been red. It\u2019s still a prevalent\nhue in bank balances.\nThat dogs never had it better,\nas witness: No pooches are al\nlowed in the giant Meramec\nCaverns at Stanton, Mo. Bui the\nmanagement has set up a special\nroom with toys where the do\u2019s\nwait in comfort while their own\ners trudge through the cave.\nThat job offers for 195! college\ngraduates are lagging far behind\nthose available to the 1957 class\nat this time a year Ago.\nThat Belgian actress Monique\nvan Vooren, in debunking the idea\nthat European men are more ro\nmantic than Americans, said; \"Kis\nses have no accent.\u201d\nThat it\u2019s so cold in Siberia\nfrozen milk is sold wrapped in\npaper, just like bread.\nThat the custom of tipping one\u2019s\nhat has more behind it than male\ngallantry. As long ago as the\nCrusades armored knights raised\nthe visor of their helmets in\npassing to determine whether the\nother guy was friend or foe.\nThat it certainly was no gentle\nman who passed this remark,\noverheard in the Astor Hotel\u2019s\nHunting Room: \"I miss my wife's\ncooking\u2014whenever I can.\u201d\nThat more than 85 per cent of\nthe. drugs prescribed today were\nuflknown 20' years ago.\nThat Buenos Aires National La\nbor Chamber issued an edict say\ning: \u201cAny office girl who takes\ntime off from work to ^tave her\nnose reshaped will receive full\npay while absent. Beauty is a\nvaluable asset for working worn\nen.\nThat lightning, by combining\nELECTRICIANS\nRegular\nMEETING\nTonite, 8 P.M.\nLOCAL M\u00ab\n1.8.E.W. UNIT NO. 1\n728 Fleming St.\nnitrogen and oxygen, create 100\nmillion tons of plant food a year,\nraining down far more than is\nproduced by all the commercial\nfertilizer plants. Mother nature is\nstill the mightiest manufacturer.\nThat it was Simon Weil who\nsaid: \u201cA science which does not\nbring us nearer to God is worth\nless.\"\nVD Rate Cut\nAs State Grows\nJACKSONVILLE \u00dcB-The Flor\nida venereal disease rate, which\nm late as 1952 was double that\nof the nation, has been cut to\napproximately the national aver\nage, the State Board of Health\nreported here.\nThe board said in the decade\nfrom 1948 to 1957 the number of\nreported syphilis cases was re\nduced 64.2 per cent while the pop\nulation in the state doubled.\nThe reported number in- pri\nmary and secondary stages\u2014when\nthey are infectious to other per\nsons\u2014was cut froiq-4,837 in 1948\nto 213 in 1957.\nWater Wonderland To\nStay On Mich. Plates\nLANSING, Mich. UK Michigan\nhas decided to keep the \"Water\nWonderland\" slogan on its auto\nlicense plates for another three\nyears.\nThe state- was considering\nchanging the slogan recently and\nscores of citizens sent letters sug\ngesting new slogans.\nA Royal Oak man, disgruntled\nby the recession and its effects\non the state\u2019s economy, proposed:\n\u201cMichigan, Land of the Unem\nployed.\u201d\nAsk For Liquor Ruling\nLEXINGTON, Ky. (!)\u2014State law\nprovides no alcoholic beverages\ncan be sold while polls are open.\nBut this year there\u2019s only one\ncandidate and he\u2019s unopposed.\nSo there\u2019ll be no election. County\nofficials say they\u2019ll probably ask\nthe state attorney general for a\nruling on whether liquor can be\nsold on election day.\nTHE KEY WEST CITIZEN\nRadio and Television Listings\nCHANNEL 4 TV WTVJ\nTWVMDAI EVENING\n6:U Sport. 8:M Climax\n1:13 W\u00ab*atlwr S:M PUybouto SO*\nS:SO Renick iI:M New.\nS:4S New. 11:10 Weather\n7:00 Lone Ranter 11:15 Sporta\n7:10 Whirlybird. 11:10 Movie\n5:00 R. Diamond* 1:00 SUB OS\nnmax mornino\n0:55 Early Show i S.-SO Playhouea\n7:55 Newa, W*tber 10:00 O. Moore\n8:00 C. Kangaroo 11:00 A. Godfrey\n1 tl:\u00bb Dotto*\nFRIDAY AFTERNOON\n11:00 Noon Edition 1:30 Houaeparty*\n11:15 Secret Storm 1:00 Bls Payoff*\n11:10 Seanh 1:10 Verdict*\n13:45 Gold Llsht* 4:00 Play\n1:00 Suaie 4:10 Edge. Night*\n1:30 World Turn. 5:00 Popeye Play\n1:00 Beat Clock* 5:45 ScL FiCtlM\nCHANNEL 7 TV WCKT\nnTOBSDAX EVENING\n0:10 New.. Wther 0:30 Tenn. Ernie\n0:45 NBC New. 10:00 R. Cooney\n7:00 M Men 10:30 Jane Wyman*\n7:10 Tie Tae D*(h* 11:00 Newa\n0:00 Grooeho Man 11:15 Sport.\n8:10 Dragnet* U:M Jack Paar*\n8:00 Poo. Choice*\nFRIDAI MORNING\n0:58 Market 8:10 Today*\n7:00 Today* 0:55 News\n7:15 New. s 0:00 Romper Room\n7:10 Today* 10:00 Story A Day\n7:55 Newa 10:30 Treai. Hunt*\n0:00 Today* 11:00 Price. Right*\n0:15 Newo 11:30 Truth. Cona.*\nPoray Studio\nHOURS:\n10:00 A.M. to 7 P.M.\n404 SOUTHARD STREET\nPHONE CY 6-3088\nCHANNEL 10 TV WPST-TV\nTECBSDAY EVENING\n2 2?\u00ae^\u2019 Sbow \u201d8 McCoy.\nS:\u00bb rubles 3:00 Pat Boom\nS:M News 9:30 Navy Ix>\u00ab*\n\u00ab:4S Sports 10:00 Mak. Me\n0:35 Weather 10:X Law Saya\n7:00 TV Digest 11:00 News\n7:30 Circus Boy 11:10 Sport.\n0:00 Zorro U:3O Theatre\nFBIDAT MOENTNG\nS:W Now. 111:15 Movie\n3:30 Chapel 10:15 Theatre\n0:45 City Farmer 11:30 Trouble Fr.\n10:00 News 1\nFBIDAT AFTEBNOON\